# 1) Suppose your current working directory is ~/Desktop/classes/python_decal/. What command would allow you to navigate directly to ~/Desktop?
    # To navigate directly to ~/Desktop, I would run the command cd ~/Desktop
# 2) What does ~/ mean?
    #  ~/ is the indicator for an absolute path.
# 3) What's the difference between and absolute and a relative path in your terminal?
    # An absolute path allows you to change directories with respect to your home directory, whereas a relative path lets you create a path to change directories starting from any directory
# 4) What command would bring you back to your home directory?
    # cd 
# 5) If you called rm ./ in your current working directory, what would it do?
    # It would get rid of everything in that directory (Source: https://gist.github.com/bradtraversy/cc180de0edee05075a6139e42d5f28ce), but I did try running that in the terminal and the following was returned: rm: "." and ".." may not be removed.
# 6) In your current working directory, what does calling "git add" do? What about "git commit"? What about "git push"?
    # Calling "git add" begins the process of adding a file or folder to the remote repository and puts it in a "staging area" (Source: Class 4 lecture slides). "git commit" will show you what changes you are making and save them to the local repository. "git push" sends what you are adding to the remote repository.
# 7) Let's say you call "git add" in your current working directory and then "git status". What message would appear? What is it telling you?
    # I am not sure what the exact message would be. In lecture, when "git status" was used after completing the process of moving a directory to the remote repository, it showed a message that there was "nothing to commit" (i.e. the local and remote repositories were identical). If you ran "git add" and then "git status", it would probably show the name of the file that you have yet to commit.
